4:["$","div",null,{"className":"prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none mb-16 [&_h2]:font-extrabold [&_h2]:tracking-tight [&_h2]:text-foreground [&_h2]:mt-12 [&_h2]:mb-4 [&_h3]:font-bold [&_h3]:text-foreground [&_h3]:mt-8 [&_h3]:mb-3 [&_p]:text-muted-foreground [&_p]:leading-relaxed [&_li]:text-muted-foreground [&_strong]:text-foreground","children":[["$","h2","h2-0",{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"The Short Answer"}],"\n",["$","p","p-0",{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4","children":"Most DAO treasuries are one of two things: idle or directionally exposed."}],"\n",["$","p","p-1",{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4","children":"The idle ones hold millions in USDC earning 1-3% on Aave. The directional ones hold their own governance token — which means treasury value crashes when the token crashes, exactly when the DAO needs resources most."}],"\n",["$","p","p-2",{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4","children":["Cross-exchange funding rate arbitrage offers a third option: ",["$","strong","strong-0",{"className":"text-foreground font-semibold","children":"market-neutral yield on deployed capital, independent of token price, without selling governance tokens."}]," It's not a treasury solution for every DAO. But for those with idle stables or excess reserves, it's worth understanding."]}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-1",{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"The DAO Treasury Problem"}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-0",{"className":"text-lg font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-3","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Most Treasuries Are Broken"}],"\n",["$","p","p-3",{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4","children":"A typical DAO treasury looks like this:"}],"\n",["$","ul","ul-0",{"className":"space-y-2 mb-4 ml-4","children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"className":"text-foreground font-semibold","children":"60-80% in governance token"}]," — value drops when the market drops, exactly when the DAO needs runway"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"className":"text-foreground font-semibold","children":"10-30% in stablecoins"}]," — sitting in a multisig or earning 1-2% on a lending protocol"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"className":"text-foreground font-semibold","children":"5-10% in ETH/BTC"}]," — directional exposure that compounds volatility"]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","p","p-4",{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4","children":"The result: in a bear market, treasury value can drop 70%+ while operational costs stay constant. Teams cut contributors, pause development, and reduce grants — all because the treasury was exposed to the same market it was trying to serve."}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-1",{"className":"text-lg font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-3","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Why Standard Yield Options Don't Work"}],"\n",["$","p","p-5",{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4","children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"className":"text-foreground font-semibold","children":"Stablecoin lending (Aave, Compound):"}]," 1-3% APY. Safe, but barely covers operational costs. A $10M treasury earning 2% generates $200K/year — not enough for most protocol teams."]}],"\n","$L9","\n","$La","\n","$Lb","\n","$Lc","\n","$Ld","\n","$Le","\n","$Lf","\n","$L10","\n","$L11","\n","$L12","\n","$L13","\n","$L14","\n","$L15","\n","$L16","\n","$L17","\n","$L18","\n","$L19","\n","$L1a","\n","$L1b","\n","$L1c","\n","$L1d","\n